# A `//` comment after the colon (Position=2 with Line=true /
# Slash.RelPos = Blank), with the value on its own line below.
#
# In the with-relpos case the comment stays on the colon's line -
# that's what the user authored, and `//` runs to end-of-line so
# the value can only follow on a new line. There must be exactly
# one break between the comment and the value, not a blank line:
# the comment and the value's leading break together contribute a
# single newline.
#
# In the norelpos case stripRelPos clears Line and Slash.RelPos,
# so the comment becomes "own-line, no specific RelPos". field()
# routes it through fieldValDoc's preVal at the value's indent
# level - which round-trips cleanly: the parser re-attaches such
# a comment as a doc of the value with Newline RelPos, and
# re-formatting produces the same indented placement. Note also
# that fields with Position=2 comments are routed to field()
# (not fieldRow) since their value can't share a line with the
# comment in a table layout - see simpleFieldChain.
-- in.cue --
d: // c
 1
-- out/relpos --
d: // c
	1
-- out/norelpos --
d:
	// c
	1
